`crates/steno/src/stroke/` is the stroke-syntax and count-bank engine used to turn a construct's numeric parameter count into a correctly merged, canonically-rendered steno stroke (e.g. `STKWR-PBGS/-FLT` + count 3 → `STKWR-PBGS/AOFLT`). Depending on this module gets you parsing/rendering of one stroke segment (`parse_stroke`/`render_stroke`, `KeySet`) and the count-bank arithmetic built on top (`count_bank`, `add_key`, `apply_count`, `merge_strokes`); nothing else in either submodule is public, so this re-exported surface is the entire contract.

`keys.rs` defines the bank model (left/mid/right key sets and their canonical orders `LEFT_ORDER`/`MID_ORDER`/`RIGHT_ORDER`) and owns the only correct notion of what counts as a left, mid, or right key. `bank.rs` builds entirely on that model — it has no independent idea of bank boundaries, so any change to `is_mid`/`is_right` or the order tables in `keys.rs` silently changes which keys `count_bank`/`add_key`/`apply_count` accept or how they render. A typical cross-file change (e.g. adding a new right-bank key) starts in `keys.rs` and must be checked against `bank.rs`'s bit-weighting and merge logic.

The shared invariant spanning both files: rendered stroke text is never safe to construct or compare via string-splicing. Hyphen placement is derived purely from whether a mid key is present in the final key set (per `render_stroke`'s asymmetry), not tracked as explicit state — so `bank.rs`'s `merge_strokes`/`apply_count`, which re-render after mutating key sets, rely on `keys.rs`'s render logic to get hyphenation right rather than reconstructing it themselves. Callers anywhere in the crate must go through `parse_stroke`/`render_stroke` for the same reason.